text: I just realized this but the reason why d3rLord3 was able to warn Avery about everything was because when he entered the Yellow Gate he saw the "The King in Yellow", The King in Yellow is a weird phenomenon but I'll just say it's an entity to make it easier to understand, anyways it's from the book "The King in Yellow" which was written by Robert W. Chambers in 1895, this book was actually what inspired H.P Lovecraft into making Cthulhu Mythos. In the story of "The King in Yellow" seeing The King in Yellow actually drives people insane, it forces their minds to take knowledge, too much knowledge. So when d3rLord3 saw The King in Yellow, he saw everything, everything that happened, everything that's happening, and everything that will be, all simultaneously and in that moment he realized that everything in existence is already laid out and because of that, he was able to know that Avery was next but all he can do is warn him.

post_title: Searching For A World That Doesnâ€™t Exist
author: @memer_nerd21610
text:
I think that d3rlord wearing a skin depicting knight in yellow, and meeting with the king in yellow is very symbolic. The king presumably gave him knowledge, symbolic of how a king commands a knight, which lead him to try to protect Avery, who he presumably only knew about because of the king's knowledge.

It's also really ironic how his perceptive nature lead him to his death? / meeting the king. I doubt most would have figured out the sign part.

This ultimately leads me to believe the king either doesnt want to found or only found by those who are perceptive enough.

But thats just a theory... A GAME THEORY! Thanks for reading :3

I guess you could say his compass was curiosity.

Parrot experienced crazy character development in this episode as well, the way he finally realized that not everyone is the way they first seem. post_title: Police Chases: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)
author: @tictacmothma
text:
I always have to tell my police chase story.
Walking in the town where I lived at the time, I was about to cross a street at a crosswalk when a car came speeding around the corner from behind me, being chased by a police car. Both ran a red light to turn into traffic that was going through the intersection at the green light. I had only just stepped into the crosswalk, so I had time to jump back onto the sidewalk safely when I heard the cars speeding from behind me, turning the corner and passing in front of me. While speeding and turning left at the red light, the police car hit a car that was going straight through the intersection at the green light. The crash killed a 5-year-old child. 

What was so important that the police officer had to put everyone on the road in danger?

I found out on the news later that day. The police were chasing a man who had stolen a bag of chips from a gas station. It wasn't even a full bag. It was one of those little pocket-size snack baggies. That's the most expensive baggie of potato chips in history, costing the life of a 5-year-old.

The police officer who killed the 5-year-old was not charged.

post_title: Police Chases: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)
author: @jakeca2
text:
FL native here, we just had 4 killed and 10+ more injured over the weekend in an FHP chase off I-275 in Tampa. They veered into the Ybor district and were still attempting PITs 2000 feet away from the main strip, which is always packed on a Friday.

Every single time I drive past the sign I canâ€™t help but think of that little boyâ€™s mother, I wonder does she have to drive past that sign and be reminded of the man who killed her son? post_title: Police Chases: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)

text:
My car was hit in a high-speed police chase, first by the perpetrator, then by the police car in pursuit!  They T-boned then flipped my car (with me in it), I was hanging upside down in my seatbelt, and had to crawl out the passenger side smashed window (with help from a kind bystander).
Nobody from the police helped me, and when they saw me standing by my car, they questioned me like I was the criminal!!  The perpetrator had stolen the car, so he had no insurance, and the police claimed zero liability. It took me a year to finally replace my car, I suffered major financial losses, physical pain, and still have PTSD (13 years later). I eventually sued the police and won, but it pretty much altered the course of my life, forever!

post_title: Police Chases: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)
author: @odderickascreations2633
text: Once worked with a guy who was a former police officer turned psych PhD.  He did a study for LAPD, that they paid him to do, on the safety of police chases, and found conclusively that no good could come of them.  The worst part was that cops became more incensed as the chase went on---an obvious human reaction largely unaccounted for in the justification of police chases.  The more angry the cop, the worse the outcome.  Innocent people get injured or killed and the "bad guys" they chase often wound up dead without a trial.  He recommended, officially, on the record, that the LAPD curtail their police chase activities.  They roundly ignored him.  And here we are.

author: @Cxrm3n
text:
Given Atsu's character and her pessimism, I kinda get why she didn't immediately jump into her brother's arms. 
First she's in shock that someone she thought dead was actually alive all this time. Then there's the fact that he was cared for, fed, nursed to health, and had people to help him while she was on her own, fended for herself, treated as less than for being a woman with a sword. She probably would've loved to have her brother by her side with everything she endured on her own. She lost her family, people who meant a lot to her, so it's obvious she's scared of letting people get close again for fear of losing them too. She probably blames herself for her parents death as well.
It was Jubei's decision to not go home because that's how he chose to grieve, but Atsu might resent it because it kept them apart for so long.

I think it's realistic that they didn't immediately act like they were so close because they don't know each other fr. Neither of them know exactly what the other went through and Atsu is kinda right in saying one night isn't going to change that.

Add to the fact that Jubei is allied with the Matsumae clan who don't believe women could be samurai, she doesn't know where his beliefs lie anymore given the treatment she got from other members of the same clan.

Is media literacy really deadğŸ˜­?

post_title: Who is this person? | Ghost of Yotei [4]
author: @A.26Films
text:
1:30:58 I'm a culture nerd so here's some cultural/historical context for Atsu's lack of affection with her brother:

(â€¼I understand that she's also carrying resentment for him because of the circumstances, this is just cultural context to explain why she probably wouldn't have been that "affectionate" by Western standards even if she wasn't angry with him.)

The colonization of Ezo began around 1869, at which point physical affection, both public and private, between relatives was not custom in Japan. 

Things like hugging, hand-shaking, kissing, and even saying "I love you", were not adopted into Japanese social customs until the 1940s-1950s from the US occupation. 

Like most east Asian countries, Japanese people express their affections more indirectly through acts of service, writing, gifting, etc. I'm half-Asian, so I can confirm first-hand that this cultural difference is still very much prevalent today.

Finally got all that yap out, if you're still reading thanks ig! :)

text:
Personally, I suspect Herrah's advice to Hornet came from a realization that, in birthing Hornet for the purpose of completing the Weavers' ultimate goal, Herrah herself had become no better than her own mother. At least, that is an interpretation that feels in line with the story's theme, and a fitting setup for the sentiment Hornet ends the dream with, as well as Grand Mother Silk's final sacrifice for the chance that Lace may live on.

Also, I am quite disappointed you didn't find the time to slip in a single mention of Twelfth Architect commenting on Hornet's "affinity for radial blades."

post_title: The (Somewhat) Complete Lore of Silksong
author: @SugarBombChar
text:
Motherhood is a large theme in this game.

Shakra's storyline, we find out, leads to her mother who she respected more as a master; Hornet's memory of her mother being both tragic and beautiful - her advice being to seek her own path while Hornet not being able to really recall her face; Grandmother Silk's love for Lace meanwhile her neglect of Phantom; Huntress's side quest; Hornet confronting the White Lady in her memory - not the Pale King; Many of the Journal Entries; Even the first boss you fight is the Moss Mother. What to conclude from that, I have no idea.

post_title: Man prepares to finish walk around the world that took 27 years
author: @Reingemurkst
text:
My parants spent their honeymoon cycling through Patagonia. They once told me about a guy they met along the way, who's plan was to "walk home" to England. I showed this video to them today. Turns out they met Karl just 4 Months after he started his journey. They thought he would never make it home alive, so it was a big surprise for them to find out he still exists and is still continuing his journey

Edit: 
My mom just sent me a page of here diary from when they met Karl. She wrote that he didn't really seemed to be exited about his journey. He seemed bitter. Watching this feels inspiring but thats not how my parents felt after meeting Karl. My mom described the way she felt after meeting him as if she just came back from a funeral.

post_title: Raccoons Are Evolving Similarly To Dogs!
author: @Orion1015
text:
I used to have "pet" wild raccoons.  They lived in the woods behind my house.  They kept coming up on my porch and sitting outside the back door until I'd feed them, which I would do.

When rival raccoons moved in, or predators were around, they would come up on the porch and literally hide behind me for safety.  When they had babies, they brought them to meet me, and the babies would play on/around the porch, even when I was outside.

They babies were raised around me, and were used to me.  I even let them into the house from time to time, and they were extremely well behaved.

post_title: Public Media: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)
author: @EB-vw9zw
text: Public radio has absolutely saved and changed my life. I was homeless for over a decade and I do not think I would have survived without public radio. The weather report being available all day, the local emergency coverage, the availability of cheap pocket radios/ free radio apps that work without a phone plan or wifi/data or subscription, the involvement in community affairs that makes you feel like part of a community even when you are on the outskirts, and the human connection provided by the stories told on the radio, and the radio stories recounted to others to give a point of connection with people who otherwise may feel they have very little in common with the unhoused. All were curtial to my mental health and determination to keep going. And that's just public radio in general, not the specific radio shows they play, which actively taught techniques for difficulties,  such as relieving anxiety, or personal stories of struggle that inspired me to get out of bed everyday or stay positive. I cannot thank you enough, Public Radio. ğŸ§¡

post_title: Public Media: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)
author: @miraahnthewall
text: When I worked on a fishing boat in Alaska years ago, the local radio station used to have a service where friends and family of people out fishing could call in to pass messages to us through a daily broadcast. This was especially helpful because there wasn't any cell phone coverage in the area, so we would tune in at noon everyday to hear messages from people onshore. I think it was called something like "fishing grams." It would often be things like "Suzanne has invited the crew of the Loon over for dinner tonight, as they have extra halibut." They also helped organize the community to search for a missing girl, who was later found in the woods.

post_title: Public Media: Last Week Tonight with John Oliver (HBO)
author: @dtkeyx
text: I was a volunteer DJ on KRZA back in 2010ish, for about 6 months.  It truly was community radio run by and for the people of Alamosa, Colorado.  A lovely little station that is one of the only resources for a lot of folks in that very isolated area.  As volunteer DJs we basically got to host and play whatever music we wanted and talk about whatever we wanted.  It was a great experience for me and my co-hosts.  Thanks for all you do KRZA and Last Week Tonight!

author: @RFineOnline
text: The neighborhood cat gave birth randomly in my cupboard one day and had 6 babies. When I came home I saw something outside in the walkway and picked it up and it was one of the kittens still in the bag so small and tiny. I brought it inside and opened the bag and he wasn't breathing and he was so cold and small I was sure he was dead but I quickly got him onto a little heating pad and kept my hands on him for almost an hour to try heat him up. Against all odds he had started breathing very shallow and looking for milk. I tried to let him drink by mom but she immediately bit him and scooted him away. I took him with me holding him against my bare skin to the vet to get formula and came home and fed him. He was easily half the size of the other kittens and had many problems right in the beginning but I never let him slip away. I have had him now for 16 years and he is still absolutely attached to me and the biggest black tuxedo cat you will ever see!!! I love my dolliz cat â¤

post_title: WHOA! How did THIS Happen to the CAT? #funnycatvideos #catshorts #funnycats #catlovers
author: @KevGirl
text:
Sidenote to the whole "cat moms will separate out sick kittens" thing - grown cats will do this to each other, too. Sometimes cats will comfort or care for other cats that are sick, but there are also times where they will become aggressive towards the sick because of the change in scent . My two cats were pretty close the first few years I had them, then it slowly started to change. One of my cats, Lucy, became more hesitant to approach my other cat, Alice. She would also act strange and hostile around her. It happened so gradually, I didn't really notice that it was a thing until they got to a point where they both refused to share space with each other. 

Turns out, Alice had cancer. As it grew, Lucy would react to the change in Alice's scent. Looking back, knowing what I know now, it was some pretty wild stuff. So if you have cats that are close and/or bonded and one of them just suddenly starts acting differently toward the other, you might wanna keep an eye on things.

post_title: The Two Sides of Grand Theft Auto: Vice City
author: @hash-slingingslasher1374
text: My brother's girlfriend once told me a story of a time when she was lost in Miami. She literally found her way back to her hotel with nothing but her memory of Vice City. She was actually able to guide her way toward the general direction of that hotel based solely on personal memory of this primitive, highly condensed, ps2-era interpretation of Miami. Thats fucking amazing if you ask me, especially for a game this old.

post_title: The Two Sides of Grand Theft Auto: Vice City
author: @abstractspaces8186
text: My most memorable example of the AI in these earlier GTA games was in San Andreas. As I was driving like a maniac through stopped traffic I caused an NPC car to swerve and bump into another car. The second guy got out of his car and started hitting the car that collided with his car, with a baseball bat. Because of the traffic the driver couldn't escape, so the road rage guy kept hitting his car with the bat until it exploded. The killed him and blew up all the surrounding cars in a chain reaction. Then the firetruck and ambulance came everything was total chaos.

post_title: The Two Sides of Grand Theft Auto: Vice City
author: @mitsukami_FM
text:
I'm glad you touched on the textures used for shopfronts, especially those in the mall. One thing that has fascinated me about GTA 3 - 5 is knowing that the images used for these shop textures are, more likely than not, photos taken by Rockstar's location scouts. In some of these shopfront photos, there are times where I've noticed actual people within them. I think about the fact that these seemingly unimportant textures are comprised of employees and shoppers who may or may not still be living but are now forever immortalized within a moment in time that was captured by some random photographer on a regular day, 10-20 years ago. 

It makes the games feel a little more eerie but also more lived in when I think about that aspect of the environmental design of these games.

post_title: The Two Sides of Grand Theft Auto: Vice City
author: @AgentB7
text: With the cops chasing those guys in leather jackets, thereâ€™s a curious unintentional tidbit. When an NPC gets killed, thereâ€™s often an ambulance dispatched to the location, and the paramedics can even revive them. So Iâ€™ve seen once or twice them locking into an endless cycle: a cop kills a guy, paramedics come, revive him, the cop starts chasing him again, kills again, paramedics revive him againâ€¦ and that continues until something breaks the cycleâ€¦ or not.

text: Im 33 and have lived in Miami since I was 14. Talking about the 2 worlds of Vice City really hits home. Everyone knows us for our beaches and nightlife but even though we may enjoy it from time to time, the average Miami citizen is only in that part of town if they are working. Thats tourist zone and its pretty and shiny. The less looked at, and the reality for most of us are places like Hialeah and Little Havana.

author: @OmegaYeet123
text:
SML ideas:

SML Movie: The New Gen Avengers! Junior becomes Juni-or (Junior Thor), Joseph becomes Captain Freedom, Jeffy becomes Iron Jeffy, Cody becomes The Hunk, Ken becomes Spider Ken, and Penelope becomes The Violent Witch! The villains are Bully who becomes Bullytron, Brooklyn Guy who becomes Dr Guy, and Chef Pee Pee who becomes Chefnos

SML CHOOSE YOUR ADVENTURE!

ReawaKEN: The plot is that overnight, Cody and Ken switch bodies. This leaves Cody's body as a non-sentient husk, which is kept on life support while Cody's mind is in Ken's body, but unable to move. Junior and Joseph have 24 hours to figure out how to put Cody back in his body.

Jeffy Fiction (pulp fiction parody): this is mainly just for the "aww I shot Marvin in the face" thing....Logan can make the plot!

Sml movie: Joseph's big decision (2-part video) on Joseph's birthday, his mom remembers him and feels bad for abandoning him after winning the lottery so she decides to see him one last time so he can meet his new family, after a day with Joseph she wants him to live with her again. Junior finds out and works together with the other characters to keep Joseph with them then Joseph has to make a big decision, to stay or go.........he stays.

shoryuKEN

Camil Habib Habab

The Life Of Jackie Chu

Jeffy The Prankster

Joseph's cousin

Jeffy Goes Skateboarding

Richard The Rapper

Joseph's Brother

SmoKEN

ChoKEN

Jeffy's Daddy Problems

Goodman's House Arrest: Goodman is put under house arrest at Marvin's house for trying to get Marvin's house payment, despite how Does Bad Things Guy gave him the house for free. Goodman finally learns humility right at the end of the episode, but then is released from house arrest, and immediately goes back to forcing Marvin to give him a house payment.

Goodman's Backstory: Goodman has a memory about his life and how he got rich AF!

Purple Jeffy / Junior: Jeffy or Junior breaks their bed so their parents decide to get them the new purple mattress only sleep on it during the night but they do sleep on it during the day and accidentally turn purple!

TOKEN: Junior and his friends go to the arcade and Cody accidentally gets Ken stuck in a claw machine and needs a "toKEN" to get out!

SML Movie: Jeffy's DeLorean'

JoKEN

BaKEN!

DRUNKEN!

The Haunted House!

Rose's Mistake: "Rose takes Jeffy to McDonald's and she accidentally takes home the wrong kid!" Description by @Green SonicKid

post_title: SMGs are BORING...
author: @Ğ’Ğ°Ğ¹Ğ¿ĞµÑ€Ğ Ğ°Ğ·Ğ´Ğ²Ğ°Ñ‚Ñ€Ğ¸
text:
Donâ€™t want to ruin anyoneâ€™s mood, but in the history part of video, at least the ww1-2 part, the author got almost Every Single Thing Wrong. And a few moments in later history too.

Making short list of mistakes and misconceptions:
1. The mp-18 was build without any influence of Thompson, and actually got in other general direction, they share almost nothing in common aside from general concept. And mp-18 due to their simpler manufacturing and construction saw the battlefield first(they even use the old Luger drum mags to make weapon cheaper). 
2. Most of the smg's of world war 2, aside from Thompson in America and beretta smg line in Italy(starting from beretta-1918, being second smg that seen combat in ww1, but Iâ€™m not sure if itâ€™s exact weapon, cause in not so good at Italian weapons), and maybe other countries I donâ€™t remember: all other construct their weapons under direct influence of mp-28. 
-the Brits at first came out with the Lancchester submachine gun, as slightly simplified mp-28, that later turned into sten, as even more simplified gun when they seen that wartime production could not made enough Lanchesters to feed the entire army
-Japanese use mp-28 as base for creation of their type 100 machine gun that they use through all of ww2
-Soviets use PPD-34 as first mass production smg for red army(as far as I know), and also draw a heavy influence from mp-28, but it at first use the stick mag, that was placed under the gun. The idea of drum mag comes to mind of Soviet constructors after the 1939 winter(Finland-Soviet) war - where they seen use of Finnish Suomi(also based around mp-28 construction) submachine gun, that used 71 round drum mag in that period. Learning from that experience, the usovieta adapt this design of the magazine and PPD-40, next modification of PPD line comes with the same 71 round drum magazine, that later was used in the PPSH
3. Germans DID NOT heavily use the mp-40 on army scale, as they relied on different tactics of warfare. While soviets and Americans mostly use smg's(or in case of Americans also a BAR machine guns) as their main source of automatic firepower, the Germans rely on machine gun crew in every troop squad, equiped at for ports with mg-13, and later with mg-39 and 42 machine guns. Thatâ€™s why mp-40 was mostly handed to lower rank officers, tanks and machines crews as their main weapon, while the regular troops through much of the war used standard Kar98 and gewehr bolt-action rifles(to be fair, as soviets try to arm as much of their men with submachine guns as possible(mostly in form of old PPD's, PPSH's and lesser known Leningrad production PPS's) after the start of the war when attempt to rearm the army for Semi-automatic SVT-86 rifles failed, big part of the army still used the bolt action mosin-nagant rifles in different variations even at the end of the war in 1945). They tried to fix it only in later part of the war, with construction of their StG-44, the first and only working wonder weapon, but it come a bit to late in war to really mass produce to a whole army at that point.
4. Americans did not abandon Thompson entirely, to go with m3 grease guns, they mostly sullied in parallel to the army, while grease gun have a much simpler construction - the Thompson was also redesigned into much simpler construction with m1 variation, that saw mass use in the army, that mostly got supplemented with others smg's due to even m1 not having enough production to supply the whole army
5. Sterling smg's DID NOT made after the creation of uzi. The first models of Sterling smg, as â€œupraiseâ€ of sten gun was first worked on in finishing months of ww2, and like tomson in ww1 didnâ€™t make it to the front lines before the end of the war, and thatâ€™s why its adoption by the army was delayed by several years while Britain, like most of European countries. deals with post war economic crisis

post_title: SMGs are BORING...
author: @inquisitorbenediktanders3142
text:
3:20 alright, I am not well read on the P90's development history, but there are several errors I found here: 
1st the PDW was first and foremost meant as a weapon for rear-line troops that aren't expected to fight, primarily as a response to counter soviet paratroopers, whose body armor was generally thought of to be fairly good at defeating standard 9x19mm parabellum. Law enforcement and the like were not the expected users.
2nd There were several different entries by more companies than just FN and H&K, tho these two were the furthest in development.
3rd the story afterwards is nowhere near as clear cut. The entire thing was very messy and chaotic, and in the end it went away with the soviet union, like several other weapon development programs during that time.
Both the P90 and the MP7 have found their own uses in militaries, law enforcement and private security companies, but standardization on one specific PDW within NATO is probably not gonna happen any time soon.
4th the price. H&K is well known for selling their weapons at very high prices, but guess what: so does FN. Both are complicated firearms with all the newest bling of their respective times, each firing their own proprietary cartridge. While official prices are hard to come by, given that you can't just order one from a catalogue, the idea of the P90 being five times cheaper than the MP7 is plain ridiculous.

My own sources are the youtube Channels Forgotten Weapons, 9Hole Reviews and Harold. All 3 have covered this topic.

text: Not a regular viewer here: this was a banger. Well argued and succinct, and good to see a creative with a large platform taking an actual stance on the use of generative AI in games. I'm a member of a handful of creator programs myself, and my concerns about AI generated content have been met with resistance and conflict avoidance. my peers in the field mysteriously piping up to be like "wow, things are getting heated in here" because I brought up criticism of generative AI, as though critique itself was the issue. text: Responding from the UK, I am appalled at this latest 'deal' from DT, in fact it's so unbelievable as to make one believe it's a spoof; however, every metric out there screams not to reward a country for violently invading an adjoining neighbour and slaughtering thousands of it's citizens and their soldiers not forgetting the medieval action of kidnapping Ukrainian children. Military History is one of my main hobbies and if it teaches us anything, it's that you never willingly surrender to tyrants. The only honourable response is to stick two fingers up in a Churchillian gesture, as he did in June 1940 and in doing so inspired the whole country to fight on rather than surrender to the monstrous Nazi regime. Also worth remembering that by 1940 Stalin had already deliberately inflicted famine on the Ukraine when close to 4 million died as a result, the Germans then 'liberated' the Ukraine during Operation Barbarossa in the summer of 1941 for the welcoming Ukrainians to find out that they'd lost one tyrannical regime to be replaced by an equally evil one. This latest attempt to subjugate the Ukrainians is to me is utterly shameful and as a Brit, I join with you good US folk in heartedly rejecting out of hand, this supposed 'peace deal'. Thankfully and hopefully, it seems at last that both sides of your Congress have simply at long last had enough and are pushing back on this, joining Europe and the members of NATO who are joining the fight. End of Sunday evening rant!

Full disclosure, I am Swedish. But to me, the real decision is about sovereignty. Either Canada buys fighters that only run if Lockheed says so, or you build Gripen jets with minimal to zero secrets and a commitment of tech-transfer, so that every Canadian Gripen is only Canadian, not dependent on daily software deliveries from the US.
Another thing, if Canada buys F-35s, the US will know every flight and every mission the F-35 undertakes as the plane needs specialized "mission files" tailored to train and mission, only Lockheed can make those, and that means the US knows about every Canadian flight. With Gripen Canada do all that themselves
